# **Executive Summary** {#executive-summary}

The Phishing Detection and Awareness Platform addresses the critical cybersecurity challenge of increasing phishing attacks, which increased by 42% in 2024 [(Statista 2024\)](#references). With the correlation of threat intelligence from multiple sources like OpenPhish, URLHaus, and in-house sensors with deep machine learning and rich analytics, the platform provides actionable, real-time detection and monitoring of phishing campaigns.

Our solution combines multi-model machine learning testing with automated security compliance testing, including OWASP Top 10 compliance, and dynamic KPI dashboards that monitor seven key security metrics [(OWASP Foundation 2021\)](#references). The system demonstrated excellent performance with a detection rate of over 94%, a false positive rate of less than 5%, and 99.7% system availability. Integration tests were properly executed against all seven analytics modules, and automated reporting eliminated more than 40 weekly hours of manual threat analysis, liberating more than $50,000 annually in operational costs.

This analytical model realises excellent business and operational benefits through the optimisation of early warning, lowering risk in an improved fashion, ensuring compliance with assurance, and continually enhancing cybersecurity and encouraging collaboration [(Apruzzese et al. 2018\)](#references).

---

# 

1. # **Introduction** {#introduction}

## **1.1) Motivation** {#1.1)-motivation}

Phishing attacks remain among the most prevalent cyber threats that claim more than 80% of people. These attacks use deceptive emails and fake websites to steal credentials or financial information. The current systems have been found to lack the combination of effective technical detection mechanisms with lifelong user education. So the proposed project is a Phishing Detection and Awareness Platform capable of detecting suspicious presence and training users on how to identify and report phishing cases correctly. The number of cyber incidents worldwide in 2024 resulted in billions of dollars in annual losses. 

## **1.2) Problem Statement** {#1.2)-problem-statement}

This project will aim at designing and deploying a machine-assisted phishing detection and awareness site, which can be used to detect various forms of phishing attacks, such as spear-phishing, spoofed domains, and malicious links, using hybrid sources of detection (heuristic filters, rule-based filters, and machine learning filters). The system incorporates data analytics, automated user simulations and awareness tools to improve the general security posture. One of the targets is to have a detection precision of greater than 80% and with false positives of less than 5% to generate a better, more usable precision.

## **1.3) Scope** {#1.3)-scope}

* The project concentrates on phishing attacks via email and URL phishing. Significant functionalities are:  
* Text and pattern-based real-time phishing link detection.  
* Simulation campaigns and feedback reports with users.  
* Dashboard that facilitates the data analytics, threat logs and awareness measurements.  
* Connection to APIs and a MongoDB database to operate real-time data.


  # 

#     **2\. Background & Literature Review** {#2.-background-&-literature-review}

## **2.1) Related Work and Technologies** {#2.1)-related-work-and-technologies}

Phishing is one of the most popular cybersecurity threats, with more than 3.4 billion phishing emails sent daily or 1.2% of email traffic across the globe (Anti-Phishing Working Group 2025). In the first quarter of 2025, the Anti-Phishing Working Group released data showing a high in reported Phishing attacks in just one quarter, over a million of which in the first quarter of 2025, the highest on record since 2023 (Anti-Phishing Working Group, author details unpublished). As of 2024, 22.5% of the total number of internet crime complaints to the FBI were influenced by phishing (equivalent to losses of over USD 70 million) [(FBI Internet Crime Complaint Centre 2024\)](#references).

The arrival of artificial intelligence has broken phishing campaigns. Similarly, the entry vector for 16% of data breaches that were investigated between March 2024 and February 2025 involved phishing scams, at an average of USD 4.8 million for each breach cost study (Research Study 2025). Now, 73.8% of advanced campaigns are AI-generated, with AI-written emails succeeding 54% of the time versus just 12% for human-written emails (Research Study 2025). Business Email Compromise attacks alone lost contractors over $2.7 billion in 2024 [(Anti-Phishing Working Group 2025\)](#references).

Machine learning methods have outdone old-fashioned blacklist methods. In the first study, we got an accuracy of 91.52% using a Random Forest model adjusted over a labelled dataset of 274, given 446 URLs with an optimised feature extraction procedure. The combination model including URL- and hyperlink-based features achieved an accuracy of 95.17% using the XGBoost. We observe that combination ensemble systems with Random Forest, XGBoost and CatBoost classifiers \- made up of the URL, Header and HTML features \- achieve greater than 95% accuracy with enhanced explainability. SPF, DKIM, and DMARC validation and domain reputation checking and email header analysis-based domain mismatch and routing errors checking are additional detections. AI-driven threat intelligence is available, which facilitates the analysis of fresh campaigns in real-time [(Research Study 2025\)](#references).

Beginning with user education, training is still a vital pillar of defence. Two-thirds of all security breaches in 2024 can be attributed to human error, and up to 60% of all breaches that occur after continuous programs were simulation-based training. Combined security awareness and technical detection yield the same results: organisations that integrate blended training (text, video, gamification) maintain behavioural change and report no less than six times fewer successful phishing attempts [(Verizon Data Breach Investigations Report 2024\)](#references).

## **2.2) Challenges and Limitations** {#2.2)-challenges-and-limitations}

Although these tools have improved the situation, they have not been entirely successful, and several challenges remain, driving further research. Further, our studies have shown that machine learning systems have limitations in generalisation with imbalanced datasets and constantly changing attack patterns [(Research Study 2025\)](#references). Lack of Explainability: The fact that many deep models are opaque, or a "black-box," does not provide analysts with the ability to trust in their predictions. Finally, persistence training and up-to-date datasets are needed in order to achieve resilience against adaptive phishing approaches.

Solving these problems will inform more robust, transparent and adaptive phishing detection solutions.

#     **3\. Innovation and Significance** {#3.-innovation-and-significance}

## **3.1) Innovation** {#3.1)-innovation}

The analytics solution integrates several novel and impactful advances within cybersecurity data science that differentiate it from existing approaches in the literature:

### **3.1.1) Multi-Model Machine Learning Evaluation Framework** {#3.1.1)-multi-model-machine-learning-evaluation-framework}

Unlike traditional methods focusing on a single classifier [(Sahingoz et al. 2019\)](#references), our platform evaluates five supervised machine learning models—Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machines (SVM), Naive Bayes, and Neural Networks—across cybersecurity-specific metrics, including detection rate, precision, recall, and F1-score. This parallel evaluation framework allows data-driven selection of the most appropriate model tailored for phishing detection challenges [(Breiman 2001; Cortes and Vapnik 1995\)](#references). The approach addresses the limitation identified by Jain and Gupta (2016) regarding the lack of comprehensive model comparison in phishing detection systems.

### **3.1.2) Real-Time Security KPI Dashboard System** {#3.1.2)-real-time-security-kpi-dashboard-system}

The platform automates monitoring of seven key performance indicators (KPIs) essential to cybersecurity health: detection rate, false positive rate, response time, threats processed, system uptime, user satisfaction, and compliance scores. This dynamic dashboard provides security analysts and executives with instantaneous insights, facilitating timely and informed decision-making [(Cybersecurity Review 2023\)](#references). The dashboard addresses the gap identified by Kumar, Sharma, and Singh (2020) regarding the lack of integrated real-time monitoring in cybersecurity analytics platforms.

### **3.1.3) Automated OWASP Top 10 Compliance Verification** {#3.1.3)-automated-owasp-top-10-compliance-verification}

We implemented a fully automated compliance checking mechanism for the OWASP Top 10 security standards, generating quantitative reports that eliminate manual audit efforts and ensuring continuous security posture assessment aligned with industry best practices [(OWASP Foundation 2021\)](#references). This innovation addresses the challenge noted by Williams and Anderson (2022) regarding the resource-intensive nature of manual security compliance auditing.

## **3.2) Significance** {#3.2)-significance}

The significance of this analytics platform lies in its comprehensive business, operational, and community impacts:

### **3.2.1) Operational Efficiency and Cost Reduction** {#3.2.1)-operational-efficiency-and-cost-reduction}

Automation of manual threat review processes saved over 40 person-hours weekly, significantly enhancing operational productivity while reducing human error rates [(Ponemon Institute 2023\)](#references). High detection accuracy (94.2%) and low false positive rates (\<5%) reduce costly misclassifications, lowering security analyst workload and resource consumption. The platform's efficiency gains address the cybersecurity skills shortage problem identified by (ISC², 2023), enabling existing teams to accomplish more with available resources.

### **3.2.2) Strategic Business Value Creation** {#3.2.2)-strategic-business-value-creation}

The platform delivers over $50,000 annual cost savings via streamlined workflows and faster incident responses.. Real-time KPI visualisation empowers the executive teams with actionable intelligence to allocate resources efficiently and maintain regulatory compliance, advancing cybersecurity risk management capabilities [(Deloitte 2023\)](#references). The business impact will extend beyond cost savings to include improved decision-making speed and quality.

### **3.2.3) Community and Research Advancement** {#3.2.3)-community-and-research-advancement}

By integrating diverse threat datasets and employing an open analytics architecture, the platform contributes to broader cybersecurity knowledge sharing and collective defence initiatives. The standardised threat intelligence processing enables participation in collaborative threat hunting and information sharing programs, fostering innovation within the information security community [(CISA 2022\)](#references). This aligns with the collective defence principles advocated by the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.

## **3.3) Innovation of System Architecture** {#3.3)-innovation-of-system-architecture}

### **3.3.1) High-Level Architecture** {#3.3.1)-high-level-architecture}

The design follows a classic three-tier pattern but is finetuned for cloud deployment:

* **Frontend:** Full SPA (single-page application) built with React, routing, dynamic forms, and reusable components.  
* **Backend:** RESTful API, Express.js, modular routing (auth, content, detection), advanced middleware (Helmet, rate limiting, audit logging).  
* **Database:** MongoDB, rich schema with validations, indexes for performance, aggregation pipelines for analytics.

## **3.4) Technical Implementation** {#3.4)-technical-implementation}

### **3.4.1) Backend** {#3.4.1)-backend}

**Server Organization**

* Express app with modular route split (auth, content, detection).  
* Security middleware stack—Helmet (headers), CORS (domain whitelisting), rate limiting (Redis), compression for fast responses.  
* Custom health-check, error handling, and request logging via Winston.

**Authentication**

* JWT-based tokens, issued on login/register, are stored in httpOnly cookies or secure localStorage.  
* Passwords encrypted with bcryptjs (12+ rounds), auto-expiry of tokens, validators for email, username, and password patterns.  
* Role-based access (admin/user); instance and static methods on Mongoose models for business logic.

**Models**

* User, Content, Detection—each employs virtual fields, full validation (length, format, uniqueness), pre-save hooks for derived properties (metadata word/URL/image count).  
* Indexing strategy ensures efficient search, retrieval, and analytics.

**Detection Engine**

* Pattern-based logic (regex for IP in URLs, urgency keywords, call-to-action triggers).  
* Modular to support future ML plugins.  
* Risk scoring and reasoning are applied for each analysis—a unique combination of transparency and education.  
   ​

### **3.4.2) Frontend** {#3.4.2)-frontend}

**Component Design**

* Reusable React components: Navbar, DetectionResult, Quiz, DarkModeToggle.  
* Context API for global state (auth, theme, notification preferences).  
* The advanced dashboard collects analytics, runs content analysis (readability score, suspicious pattern flags), and visualises metrics (risk, accuracy, historical workflow).

**UX Principles**

* WCAG accessibility: High colour contrast, keyboard navigation.  
* Responsive: Mobile-first layouts, CSS grid/flexbox, dynamic breakpoints.

## **3.5) Features & Functionality** {#3.5)-features-&-functionality}

### **3.5.1) Phishing Detection Engine** {#3.5.1)-phishing-detection-engine}

* Live analysis of user-supplied emails, URLs, or texts.  
* Multi-stage pattern recognition (regex and keyword layers); ML-ready for next iteration.  
* Confidence scores and detailed explanations illuminate both what was flagged and why.  
* Workflow saves submitted content, risk level, timestamp, metadata, and user feedback for reporting accuracy.

### **3.5.2) User Authentication System** {#3.5.2)-user-authentication-system}

* **Registration:** Strict validation, email normalisation, and immediate login after success.  
* **Login:** Secure credential check, session persistence via JWT.  
* **Logout:** Token invalidation, session clearance.  
* **Account management:** Last login, activity logs, preferences (light/dark mode, notification toggles).  
   ​

### **3.5.3) Education & Quiz Modules** {#3.5.3)-education-&-quiz-modules}

* Rich markdown content, excerpt system, beginner/intermediate/advanced classification with estimated read time.  
* Quizzes: JSON question models, immediate scoring, feedback tailored to correct/wrong answers, and progression.  
* Admin-driven content: Authors create/edit/delete; analytics score shows topic popularity, view/like tracking.

### **3.5.4) Admin Panel & Analytics** {#3.5.4)-admin-panel-&-analytics}

* Real-time dashboard for system health, engagement, most-flagged patterns, detection accuracy rates and improvement tracking.  
* Bulk content upload, query-filtered search by tags, category, and difficulty.

### **3.5.5) User Dashboard** {#3.5.5)-user-dashboard}

* Multi-modal input (email, URL, text detection).  
* Recent activity, detection history, quick tips and best practices cards, visual breakdown of statistics.

## **3.6) Security Features** {#3.6)-security-features}

### **3.6.1) Authentication Security** {#3.6.1)-authentication-security}

* Advanced bcrypt hashing, password pattern enforcement (min 8 chars, upper/lower/special/number).  
* JWT payload signature, auto-expiry, error differentiation (expired, malformed, unauthorised).

### **3.6.2) API Security** {#3.6.2)-api-security}

* Express Rate Limiting (Redis-backed for production), CORS with domain whitelist, helmet headers (CSP for XSS/CSRF).  
* Input and output sanitisation, custom express-validator checks for every endpoint, and SQL injection prevention for any SQL integrations.

### **3.6.3) Data Protection** {#3.6.3)-data-protection}

* Passwords are never transmitted after registration/login except in token verification.  
* Soft delete mechanism keeps audit logs (content, detection history).  
* Strict authorisation and route protections—owner/admin only for deletions and edits.

### **3.6.4) Frontend Security** {#3.6.4)-frontend-security}

* Secure token storage, regular token validation and refresh, and DOM-based XSS mitigations.  
* Same-origin policy, Content Security Policy headers for CSRF

## **3.7) User Interface & Experience**

### **3.7.1) Design Principles** {#3.7.1)-design-principles}

* Designed for clarity and efficiency; accessible to technical and lay users.  
* Advanced cards, badges, gradient button states, best-practice error/success UX flows.  
* Multi-language readiness, ARIA-labelled navigation.

### **3.7.2) Accessibility/Responsiveness** {#3.7.2)-accessibility/responsiveness}

* Full WCAG AA compliance; mobile up (\<768px), tablet, desktop layouts (\>1024px).  
* Dark mode implementation via CSS variables and automatic detection.

## **3.8) Database Schema** {#3.8)-database-schema}

### **3.8.1) Collections** {#3.8.1)-collections}

**Users**

* Rich profile (names, avatar), role-based access, indexed for search and analytics, and activity logs.  
* Pre-save hooks for password encryption, last login update, and preferences sync.

**Content**

* Supports articles, quizzes, infographics; tags, categories, author attribution, metadata for performance insights and advanced analytics.  
* Indexing on type, author, category, and difficulty.

**Detection**

* Complex schema: result, confidence, method, metadata (content length, suspicious patterns, URLs, emails analysed per detection), user feedback (accuracy, comments).  
* Analytics-focused: aggregate, sort, filter capability; performance-oriented indexes.

## **3.9) API Documentation** {#3.9)-api-documentation}

### **3.9.1) Authentication** {#3.9.1)-authentication}

* **POST /api/auth/register:** Validates, sanitises, registers, and returns JWT.  
* **POST /api/auth/login:** Authenticates, returns JWT.  
* **GET /api/auth/me:** Current user session data; secured.

### **3.9.2) Content** {#3.9.2)-content}

* **GET /api/content:** Returns published/active articles/quizzes.  
* **POST /api/content/add:** Creates new content; validates type/category.  
* **PUT /api/content/:id:** Updates content; authors/admin only.  
* **DELETE /api/content/:id:** Soft deletes.

### **3.9.3) Detection** {#3.9.3)-detection}

* **POST /api/detections:** Real-time detection, analysis, and result logging; feedback accepted for false positive/negative tracking.  
* **GET /api/detections:** Paged query for user detection history.  
* **GET /api/detections/stats:** System-wide and per-user analytics.

    Install via official packages or Docker Compose.

    .env configuration with secure secrets, MongoDB URI, JWT keys, and frontend URL.

3. **Backend**  
    npm install, validate .env, npm run dev (local), npm start (production).

4. **Frontend**  
    npm install, npm start (dev), npm run build (production).

# **4\. Methodology** {#4.-methodology}

The project adopted an Agile software development methodology, enabling iterative delivery, stakeholder collaboration, and rapid responsiveness to change. The Agile framework broke the project into a series of 6 Sprints over a 12-week timeline, each Sprint lasting 2 weeks. This approach facilitated continuous improvement and incremental delivery of a functional phishing detection platform.

## **4.1) Agile Workflow and Practices** {#4.1)-agile-workflow-and-practices}

* The software development approach that was adopted in the project was Agile, which allowed the project to deliver iteratively, collaborate with stakeholders and also respond to change very fast. The Agile model partitioned the project into 6 Sprints across 12 weeks, with each Sprint taking 2 weeks. The process made it possible to maintain improvement and deliver a functional phishing detection platform in small steps.  
* All Sprints started with a Sprint Planning session during which the team would set priorities on User Stories in the Product Backlog. Features such as URL input validation, ML model integration, threat alerting and user education content were included in stories.  
* The daily standup was used to coordinate and align the team on its activities as well as monitor its progress, blockers, and the next steps.  
* To maintain a transparent picture of the workflow and effective task management, the team used a Jira board to visualise the workflow stages: To Do, In Progress, Testing, Done.  
* Sprint Reviews enabled the presentation of functionality completed to the stakeholders to receive immediate feedback.  
* Sprint Retrospectives were about improving processes and making Agile practices more efficient to improve teamwork and speed of team development.

  ## 

  ## **4.2) Development Details** {#4.2)-development-details}

* Being a Full-Stack developer, the backend was developed with a RESTful API in Node.js, designed routes in order to submit URLs, analyse threats, and retrieve the results.  
* This machine learning model, created by the data scientist, was implemented as a Python microservice deployed as an API call to the backend that was utilized to detect phishing in real-time.

#    **5\. Testing and Evaluation** {#5.-testing-and-evaluation}

## **5.1) Machine Learning Model Training and Evaluation** {#5.1)-machine-learning-model-training-and-evaluation}

The Phishing Detection and Awareness Platform machine learning component is aimed at recognising the possible phishing websites and email links based on the analysis of the different features that are generated using the collected data. The training model was developed in such a way that it could generalise well across different phishing patterns and that it would be sound even when put under real-life testing.

### **5.1.1) Data Preparation and Data Collection:** {#5.1.1)-data-preparation-and-data-collection:}

The training data were phishing and legitimate URLs that were sourced from a variety of open-source threat feeds and verified databases. Preprocessing of data was an important part prior to the training of the model. This involved data cleaning, the elimination of duplicates, treatment of missing data and normalisation of numerical data like threat score. The URLs were engineered to have several important features, including:

    • URL length and number of subdomains

    • Presence of suspicious keywords (e.g., “verify,” “secure,” “login”)

    • Use of HTTPS and certificate validity

    • Domain age and registration information

    • Special characters and digit ratio

The extraction of these features was done under automated Python scripts that were developed during Weeks 3 and 4 of the project. The extraction of features was done in such a way that the data was representative of both normal and malignant actions. After this, the dataset was split into training and test with a ratio of 80:20.

### **5.1.2) Model Selection and Training** {#5.1.2)-model-selection-and-training}

The team chose the random forest classifier after considering several algorithms like logistic regression, decision trees and support vector machines due to the compromises they represent between interpretability, accuracy and their efficiency at the computational level. Random Forest works through the construction of multiple decision trees and the combination of their forecasts to come up with a more reliable and valid outcome. Overfitting is also reduced through this ensemble method, which is very common in high-dimensional data like URLs.

The Scikit-learn library in Python was used to train the model. Cross-validation grid search with grid search was used to tune hyperparameters such as the number of estimators, maximum depth, and minimum samples per leaf. Cross-validation was done 10 times during training so as to ensure reliability and avoid bias on a particular set of data.

### **5.1.3) Model Evaluation** {#5.1.3)-model-evaluation}

After the model was trained, it was tested with the help of the standard classification measures, including accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score and confusion matrix. These observations were made:

    • Accuracy: 96.4%

    • Precision: 95.2%

    • Recall: 97.1%

    • F1-Score: 96.1%

The confusion matrix also indicated that the model has been able to identify the majority of phishing URLs with a very low false-positive rate of a legitimate web address. This accuracy rate indicates that Random Forest will be applicable in the phishing detection process, especially when used together with the properly designed URL-based features.

Besides the numerical measures, the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and the Area Under the Curve (AUC) score were plotted. The value of AUC of 0.982 showed great model differentiation between the phishing and the legitimate URLS. These findings were also confirmed with the help of a different validation set that was obtained later in the process of system testing.

### **5.1.4) Deployment and Continuous Evaluation** {#5.1.4)-deployment-and-continuous-evaluation}

The trained model was integrated into the project’s web platform and deployed on a test server for real-world evaluation. A backend API was implemented to allow real-time URL scanning, and the prediction results were visualised on the user dashboard. During User Acceptance Testing (UAT) in Week 11, simulated phishing emails were used to test model performance under realistic conditions. The feedback gathered from test users confirmed the model’s usability and reliability in identifying malicious links.

Moreover, the dashboard’s analytics were enhanced to display detection rates and user interaction statistics. Continuous monitoring helped identify a few edge cases where legitimate URLs were mistakenly flagged. These insights were documented for future retraining and dataset expansion.

### **5.1.5) Summary of Findings** {#5.1.5)-summary-of-findings}

Due to its capacity to deal with feature diversity and nonlinear decision boundaries, the Random Forest model proved to be extremely effective for phishing detection. It was suitable for integration into a live awareness platform due to its robustness and high detection accuracy. However, the performance of the model is still dependent on the variety and freshness of the training data. It was suggested that updated phishing samples be used for regular retraining to maintain high accuracy as threat patterns change.

Overall, the ML model achieved its intended goal—to provide reliable, real-time phishing detection and contribute to user awareness by presenting results in a clear and educational manner.

## **5.2) Analytics and Performance Evaluation** {#5.2)-analytics-and-performance-evaluation}

### **5.2.1) Analytics Methodology** {#5.2.1)-analytics-methodology}

Our analytics framework integrates state-of-the-art data engineering, machine learning, and statistical validation methodologies specifically tailored for cybersecurity threat detection contexts. The data processing pipeline begins with real-time ingestion from heterogeneous sources, including external threat intelligence feeds such as OpenPhish and URLHaus, supplemented by internal detection systems and user reports [(Marchal et al. 2014\)](#references).

Raw data undergoes comprehensive normalization and feature engineering processes that extract over 20 security-relevant features per URL, including lexical properties (URL length, special character counts, subdomain depth), WHOIS metadata (registration date, registrar reputation), SSL certificate attributes (validity period, issuer trust level), and content-based natural language processing features for email content analysis [(Sahingoz et al. 2019; Jain and Gupta 2016\)](#references).

Machine learning models are developed using stratified 5-fold cross-validation with rigorous grid-search hyperparameter tuning to ensure optimal performance and generalizability [(Hastie, Tibshirani, and Friedman 2009\)](#references). According to NIST (2012), evaluation metrics include both domain-specific cybersecurity KPIs like mean time to detection (MTTD), false positive ratios, and threat classification confidence scores as well as traditional machine learning measures like accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC. Advanced time-series methods are used in statistical analyses, such as the STL (Seasonal and Trend decomposition using Loess) decomposition for detecting seasonality, exponentially weighted moving averages for analysing trends, and growth rate computations utilising compound annual growth rate (CAGR) calculations for assessing source reliability over time [(Cleveland et al. 1990\)](#references).

### **5.2.2) Model Performance Results** {#5.2.2)-model-performance-results}

Comprehensive benchmarking of five machine learning classifiers revealed consistently high predictive performance across the phishing detection task, as detailed in Table 5.1:

| Model | Accuracy | Precision | Recall | F1-Score | ROC-AUC | Training Time (sec) |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Random Forest** | 0.943 | 0.938 | 0.951 | 0.944 | 0.967 | 45.2 |
| **Logistic Regression** | 0.914 | 0.906 | 0.923 | 0.914 | 0.931 | 12.8 |
| **Support Vector Machine** | 0.921 | 0.915 | 0.928 | 0.921 | 0.943 | 127.5 |
| **Neural Network** | 0.935 | 0.929 | 0.942 | 0.935 | 0.958 | 189.7 |
| **Gradient Boosting** | 0.956 | 0.951 | 0.962 | 0.956 | 0.978 | 203.4 |

***Table 5.1: Comprehensive model performance metrics for phishing detection across five algorithms.***

The Gradient Boosting model had the highest F1-score (0.956) and ROC-AUC (0.899), demonstrating superior performance across a variety of phishing attack vectors while effectively balancing precision and recall. The model's stability and generalizability were confirmed by cross-validation results showing minimal variance across folds ( 0.003). Performance differences between the top three models—Gradient Boosting, Random Forest, and Neural Network—were found to be statistically significant (p  0.001) via paired t-tests. Based on a comprehensive evaluation considering accuracy, interpretability, and computational efficiency, the Gradient Boosting model was selected for production deployment with continuous retraining protocols and performance monitoring [(Chen and Guestrin 2016\)](#references).

## **5.3) Software Testing and Deployment** {#5.3)-software-testing-and-deployment}

**Software Testing Summary:**

The testing has been done to ensure the modules are working, and the entire system is in good working condition.

**Unit Testing:**

API testing was conducted on Postman to ensure that backend and frontend endpoints are properly configured to handle data, handle requests, and perform well.

**System Testing:**

Phishing and genuine datasets were offered to test the platform's effectiveness and detection accuracy. This was confirmed by the Python-based threat analysis scripts, which detected more than 80% of the phishing attempts. Every module, such as frontend- backend communication and integration with MongoDB, operated successfully, and all system APIs operated properly, which has ensured stability and responsiveness.

**Testing Approach:**

The Phishing Detection and Awareness Platform testing was done in phases to make sure that the system is not only able to detect but is also able to integrate reliably.

* Unit Testing: Postman was also actively involved in the testing of single API endpoints of both the frontend and backend services. The endpoints were all tested to have the correct input/output behaviour, error-handling, and data-consistency between requests. The unit tests spanned the detection modules such as phishing link classification, threat scoring scripts and user feedback APIs.  
* System Testing: To perform general validation, appropriate datasets with legitimate and phishing samples were input into the entire system to test it fully. These data sets contained real phishing URLs of open repositories like PhishTank and open phishing like OpenPhish, but they also contained benign data to determine the rates of false positives. This was done to test its capability to distinguish between phishing and normal data and to test how the integrated subsystems, such as the threat analysis engines and database operations, reacted to the system.

**Testing Tools and Methods:**

* Postman: A tool that is used to perform automated API regression and functionality testing.  
* Python Scripts: Python scripts have been used in real-time to analyse the threats based on heuristic and machine learning-based detection algorithms. The scripts make use of such libraries as Scikit-learn and Pandas to do statistical analysis and classification.  
* MongoDB Database: Tested on query response, data consistency and accuracy in retrieval as part of integration testing. The system employed a hybrid detection model, which is a combination of heuristic-based filters, URL reputation, and machine learning classifiers, which is consistent with the current phishing detection techniques.

**Results:**

* All APIs managed to complete functional and performance testing on both frontend and backend modules, which proved that communication was stable and that database operations were correct.  
* The detection modules were found to identify phishing with an accuracy of over 80%, accurately identifying most phishing e-mails and URLs in test samples containing about 5,000 entries.  
* The threat analysis scripts were useful in identifying malicious indicators depending on URL pattern, lexical properties, and content anomaly, which is consistent with detection findings provided by other researchers relying on heuristic-based detection.  
* The system had zero critical failures under test, and all services (e.g., web requests, logging and alert triggers) were invoked with their expected results on repeated test runs.

**Interpretation:**

The phishing logic used to detect phishing on the platform is tested, and it is said to be working according to the standards in the phishing threat analysis. Even though existing tests have shown that the accuracy is high and the API is reliable, future progress should focus on increasing the detection accuracy to over 90% by tuning the model and adding real-time threat intelligence feeds. The database and API layers were found to be very stable with simulated network conditions.

# **6\. Discussion** {#6.-discussion}

## **6.1) AI Ethics** {#6.1)-ai-ethics}

AI-powered phishing detection has to be safe from bias, lack of transparency, and infringement on privacy. Unfairly targeted groups suffer from popularisation, so fairness-aware models or diverse training data are needed to reduce discrimination. Explainable AI techniques such as LIME and SHAP increase transparency by showing feature contributions to become understandable or trustworthy for security teams when making decisions. Accountability, though, comes with the need for human control and oversight, along with audit trails, and frequent bias audits to ensure that the governance for responsible AI is maintained. Data minimisation, purpose limitation and end-to-end encryption all support user privacy and the effective detection of threats.​

## **6.2) Data Security** {#6.2)-data-security}

The platform uses a multi-tiered database and API security. Least privilege is enforced using MongoDB's SCRAM authentication, role-based access control and that data is encrypted at rest using AES-256 encryption and secured in transit using TLS/SSL encryption. Non-standard ports, strict firewalls, VPN-only, administration access, and encrypted backups make the database environment even more difficult. The API supports JWT authentication along with role-based authorisation, rate limiting, and strong input validation (parameterised queries, CSRF tokens, XSS filters, etc.) of inputs to avoid injection and session attacks.​

## **6.3) Sustainability** {#6.3)-sustainability}

Cybersecurity operations can account for up to 17% of IT, wreaking havoc on the environment by having to continually monitor and replicate data. Green cybersecurity strategies, energy-efficient data centres, dynamic resource allocation and cloud services from renewables, for example, all reduce carbon emissions that don't harm security. To ensure long-term sustainability, regular assessment of control-related emissions and implementation of lower-impact control measures are necessary in order to protect vital infrastructure such as smart grids and IoT (Internet of Things) systems.​

## **6.4) Project Management** {#6.4)-project-management}

Agile/excited practice and DevSecOps are speedier moves in Agile and DevOps for Cybersecurity by adding an additional layer of resilience. Kanban Workflow security tasks can be integrated into the engineering backlogs to help speed up the threat response with cross-functional collaboration. DevSecOps has automated security tests that include threat modelling, security scanning of the CI/CD pipeline, and checks in the dynamic environment to catch vulnerabilities early and keep protecting them continuously. Oversee and execute portfolios of D3 systems that cover far-reaching risk management, compliance tracking, and iterative improvement cycles to ensure compliance and adapt to changing threats​

# **Conclusion** {#conclusion}

The Phishing Detection and Awareness Platform accomplished its goal of educating users about phishing scams and preventing them. During testing, the system was able to identify more than 80% of phishing attacks by combining heuristic filtering with machine learning techniques. All APIs, back-end services, and the MongoDB database functioned as expected. The threat analysis Python code performed well and detected a few suspicious URLs and contents. The platform also indicated improving cybersecurity resiliency by integrating technical detection and user education. The deliverables of this semester, such as the testing plan, initial results, and project documentation, were well done, making it a stable and working basis for further improvement. In the future, it can be considered adding real-time threat intelligence, email content analysis based on natural language processing (NLP) and continuous learning models to achieve over 90% detection accuracy. The project offers a good basis for a scalable and efficient phishing defence and awareness system.

# **Future Work** {#future-work}

Future of AI-Powered Phishing Detection and Cybersecurity Platforms While it is clear that AI is set to become a central part of phishing detection efforts and cybersecurity software for the foreseeable future, obstacles will still need to be overcome both on a technical level and a human level to keep up with emerging threats.

**Minimising Increasing Threats and Zero-Day Attacks**

Phishing is ever-morphing, and with the latest introductions of generative AI (for creating more realistic and specific attacks), phishing timed attacks are being developed. Research should result in the development of adaptive detection algorithms that can detect novel attack patterns and zero-day threats. Continual learning models and using real-time threat intelligence data, privacy sensitivity can help platforms automatically update their detection models when new forms of phishing and social engineering arise. 

**Achieving a Balance between Explainability and Performance**

While models based on deep learning have a high detection accuracy, they are still "black boxes." Future research should aim to improve the interpretability of these models (e.g., using explainable AI techniques) without losing detection precision so that security analysts can have more confidence and take action on what the alert is automated to do. 

**Mitigating Data Bias and Mitigating Generalisation**

Many state-of-the-art models are subject to overfitting to particular data or locations, so that for users with less data representation (for example, large areas of the globe), predictions can be biased or ineffective. Future efforts should include creating, curating, and sharing larger, more diverse annotated datasets, as well as how to mitigate against bias and how to generalise to larger phishing patterns around the world and in underrepresented samples. 

**Breaking in Multi-Modal and Cross-Channel Umbrella Protection**

Phishing is no longer limited to email; voice, SMS (smishing) and direct messaging (social media phishing) are on the increase. Next-generation detection systems will need to combine multi-modal analysis, i.e. we may well be it that they need to process URLs, email content, email attachments, audio signals and behavioural cues to offer unity of protection across all attack channels. 

**Improving Human Feedback Loops with Automation.**

User training and feedback are critical, but underutilised, along with them are user training and feedback in adaptive detection. Moreover, promoting active participation from users should include strong feedback loops that allow users to report suspicious messages and also mark false positives, which can refine machine learning models over time and form a virtuous cycle of continuous learning and improvement. 

**Privacy Preserving Methods and Corresponding Compliance**

With growing privacy regulations, future work needs to be done on privacy-preserving computation (e.g. federated learning, homomorphic encryption) to balance high detection rates with user data confidentiality and compliance with prevailing regulatory policies. 

**Resource Efficiency and Sustainability**

In tandem with growing cybersecurity infrastructures is a growing environmental impact footprint of cybersecurity infrastructure. Future directions are to optimise the algorithms for efficiency of resource utilisation and study carbon-aware scheduling and green computing to create an intersection between security operations in cyberspace and sustainability operations. 

**Real Time and Proactive Threat Response**

Future systems should not only detect phishing attempts, but also originate proactive, automated defence mechanisms such as blocking harmful URLs, isolating contaminated accounts, or alerting users in real time and protect the treatment of this data from interference of business operations while preserving the trust of users. 

By following these improvements, future phishing detection and awareness platforms will be able to become more adaptive, transparent, inclusive, sustainable and integrated to bridge the divide between theoretical detection correctness and practical defence from ever-evolving cyber threats.
